Q: Flutter/Dart - Using Spacer / Flexible for Column layout A: <p>The issue is your nested Columns. When you put a <code>Spacer</code> inside a Column, that Column needs to know its height. But your inner Column (in <code>myViewBody</code>) is sitting inside another Column (in <code>myView</code>) without any height constraints—so Flutter has no idea how much space the Spacer should fill.</p>
<p>Wrap <code>myViewBody()</code> with <code>Expanded</code> so the parent Column gives it bounded height:</p>
<pre><code>Widget myView() {
  return Column(
    children: &lt;Widget&gt;[
      const Text('this is the stepper view'),
      Expanded(              // &lt;-- this is the fix
        child: myViewBody(state),
      ),
    ],
  );
}
</code></pre>
<p>Hope it helps!</p>

Q: How do I mask out every bit of a number but a single random one? A: <p>At least as I understand it, you want to find the bits that are set in an input, then create a value with 1 (and only 1) of the same bits set.</p>
<p>Seems like something like this should do that:</p>
<pre class="lang-cpp prettyprint-override"><code>
#include &lt;random&gt;
#include &lt;bitset&gt;

template &lt;class T&gt;
std::vector&lt;std::size_t&gt; findSetBits(T input) {
    auto bits = sizeof(T) * std::numeric_limits&lt;unsigned char&gt;::digits;
    std::vector&lt;std::size_t&gt; set_bits;

    for (int i=0; i&lt;bits; i++) {
        if (input &amp; (1 &lt;&lt; i)) {
            set_bits.push_back(i);
        }
    }
    return set_bits;
}

template &lt;class T&gt;
T setOneBit(T input) { 
    auto set_bits = findSetBits(input);

    std::uniform_int_distribution&lt;std::size_t&gt; dist(0, set_bits.size());
    std::random_device gen;
    auto bit = dist(gen);
    return T(1) &lt;&lt; set_bits[bit];
}
</code></pre>
<p>If you were going to do this a lot, you'd probably want to use <code>random_device</code> to seed a pseudo-random generator, then use that to generate the bit you were going to set. It's usually quite a bit faster, and although it's probably more predictable, it's still probably unpredictable enough for what you seem to be doing.</p>
<p>Here's a bit of test/demo code:</p>
<pre class="lang-cpp prettyprint-override"><code>#include &lt;cassert&gt;
#include &lt;iostream&gt;

// insert functions from above here

int main() { 
    std::vector&lt;unsigned&gt; inputs { 
        0b111,
        0b101,
        0b11,
        0b10101010,
        0b01010101
    };

    for (auto i : inputs) { 
        assert(i != 0);
        int result = setOneBit(i);
        std::cout &lt;&lt; std::bitset&lt;32&gt;(i) &lt;&lt; &quot;: &quot; &lt;&lt; std::bitset&lt;32&gt;(result) &lt;&lt; &quot;\n&quot;;
        assert(result &amp; i);
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>The binary constants in the test code require C++14. The rest should be C++11 compatible.</p>

Q: Shortcode use for Advanced Custom Fields (ACF) Wordpress plugin A: <p>Do NOT use ACF’s <code>[acf]</code> shortcode here.</p>
<h3>Add this to <code>functions.php</code></h3>
<pre><code>function project_location_shortcode() {

    // WPBakery frequently runs shortcodes without loop context
    $post_id = get_the_ID();

    if (!$post_id &amp;&amp; isset($GLOBALS['post']-&gt;ID)) {
        $post_id = $GLOBALS['post']-&gt;ID;
    }

    if (!$post_id) {
        return '';
    }

    $town  = get_field('town', $post_id);
    $state = get_field('state', $post_id);

    if (!$town &amp;&amp; !$state) {
        return '';
    }

    return esc_html(trim($town . ', ' . $state, ', '));
}
add_shortcode('project_location', 'project_location_shortcode');
</code></pre>
<h3>Use this in WPBakery Text Block</h3>
<pre><code>[project_location]
</code></pre>
